[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] A parameterized problem $\Pi$ is a subset of $\Gamma ^{*}\times \mathbb {N}$ for some finite alphabet $\Gamma$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] An instance of a parameterized problem consists of *(x,k)*, where *k* is called the parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] 2. there is $\delta >0$ such that for every $(r\times r)$ -grid R , $(R,k)\not \in \Pi$ for every $k\leq \delta r^{2}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] In other words, the value of the solution on R should be at least $\delta r^{2}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Examples of minor-bidimensional problems are the parameterized versions of vertex cover, feedback vertex set, and longest path.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Let $\Gamma _{r}$ be the graph obtained from the $(r\times r)$ -grid by triangulating internal faces such that all internal vertices become of degree 6, and then one corner of degree two joined by edges with all vertices of the external face.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Examples of contraction-bidimensional problems are dominating set, connected dominating set, max-leaf spanning tree, and edge dominating set.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] All algorithmic applications of bidimensionality are based on the following combinatorial property: either the treewidth of a graph is small, or the graph contains a large grid as a minor or contraction.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] There is a function *g* such that every graph *G* excluding a fixed *h*-vertex apex graph as a minor and of treewidth at least *g(h) r* can be edge-contracted to $\Gamma _{r}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Halin's grid theorem is an analogous excluded grid theorem for infinite graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Let $\Pi$ be a minor-bidimensional problem such that for any graph *G* excluding some fixed graph as a minor and of treewidth at most *t*, deciding whether $(G,k)\in \Pi$ can be done in time $2^{O(t)}\cdot |G|^{O(1)}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Then for every graph *G* excluding some fixed graph as a minor, deciding whether $(G,k)\in \Pi$ can be done in time $2^{O({\sqrt {k}})}\cdot |G|^{O(1)}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Similarly, for contraction-bidimensional problems, for graph *G* excluding some fixed apex graph as a minor, inclusion $(G,k)\in \Pi$ can be decided in time $2^{O({\sqrt {k}})}\cdot |G|^{O(1)}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Thus many bidimensional problems like Vertex Cover, Dominating Set, k-Path, are solvable in time $2^{O({\sqrt {k}})}\cdot |G|^{O(1)}$ on graphs excluding some fixed graph as a minor.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Bidimensionality theory has been used to obtain polynomial-time approximation schemes for many bidimensional problems.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] If a minor (contraction) bidimensional problem has several additional properties then the problem poses efficient polynomial-time approximation schemes on (apex) minor-free graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] In particular, by making use of bidimensionality, it was shown that feedback vertex set, vertex cover, connected vertex cover, cycle packing, diamond hitting set, maximum induced forest, maximum induced bipartite subgraph and maximum induced planar subgraph admit an EPTAS on H-minor-free graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] A parameterized problem with a parameter *k* is said to admit a linear vertex kernel if there is a polynomial time reduction, called a kernelization algorithm, that maps the input instance to an equivalent instance with at most *O(k)* vertices.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Every minor-bidimensional problem $\Pi$ with additional properties, namely, with the separation property and with finite integer index, has a linear vertex kernel on graphs excluding some fixed graph as a minor.
[src:parameterized-complexity/bidimensionality] Similarly, every contraction-bidimensional problem $\Pi$ with the separation property and with finite integer index has a linear vertex kernel on graphs excluding some fixed apex graph as a minor.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] In the study of graph algorithms, **Courcelle's theorem** is the statement that every graph property definable in the monadic second-order logic of graphs can be decided in linear time on graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The result was first proved by Bruno Courcelle in 1990 and independently rediscovered by Borie, Parker & Tovey (1992).
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] It is considered the archetype of algorithmic meta-theorems.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The first part of this formula ensures that the three color classes cover all the vertices of the graph, and the rest ensures that they each form an independent set.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] (It would also be possible to add clauses to the formula to ensure that the three color classes are disjoint, but this makes no difference to the result.) Thus, by Courcelle's theorem, 3-colorability of graphs of bounded treewidth may be tested in linear time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The original formulation of this result required the input graph to be given together with a construction proving that it has bounded clique-width, but later approximation algorithms for clique-width removed this requirement.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Courcelle's theorem may also be used with a stronger variation of monadic second-order logic known as MSO2.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] In this formulation, a graph is represented by a set *V* of vertices, a set *E* of edges, and an incidence relation between vertices and edges.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] This variation allows quantification over sets of vertices or edges, but not over more complex relations on tuples of vertices or edges.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] However, Hamiltonicity cannot be expressed in MSO1.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] It is possible to apply the same results to graphs in which the vertices or edges have labels from a fixed finite set, either by augmenting the graph logic to incorporate predicates describing the labels, or by representing the labels by unquantified vertex set or edge set variables.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Another direction for extending Courcelle's theorem concerns logical formulas that include predicates for counting the size of the test.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] In this context, it is not possible to perform arbitrary arithmetic operations on set sizes, nor even to test whether two sets have the same size.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] However, MSO1 and MSO2 can be extended to logics called CMSO1 and CMSO2, that include for every two constants *q* and *r* a predicate $\operatorname {card} _{q,r}(S)$ which tests whether the cardinality of set *S* is congruent to *r* modulo *q*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Courcelle's theorem can be extended to these logics.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] As stated above, Courcelle's theorem applies primarily to decision problems: does a graph have a property or not.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] However, the same methods also allow the solution to optimization problems in which the vertices or edges of a graph have integer weights, and one seeks the minimum or maximum weight vertex set that satisfies a given property, expressed in second-order logic.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] These optimization problems can be solved in linear time on graphs of bounded clique-width.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] In particular, it is possible to recognize the graphs of bounded treewidth, and any MSO property on these graphs, by a deterministic Turing machine that uses only logarithmic space.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The typical approach to proving Courcelle's theorem involves the construction of a finite bottom-up tree automaton that acts on the tree decompositions of the given graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] This is an equivalence relation, and it can be shown by induction on the length of *F* that (when the sizes of *T* and *F* are both bounded) it has finitely many equivalence classes.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] A tree decomposition of a given graph *G* consists of a tree and, for each tree node, a subset of the vertices of *G* called a bag.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] It must satisfy two properties: for each vertex *v* of *G*, the bags containing *v* must be associated with a contiguous subtree of the tree, and for each edge *uv* of *G*, there must be a bag containing both *u* and *v*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The vertices in a bag can be thought of as the terminals of a subgraph of *G*, represented by the subtree of the tree decomposition descending from that bag.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] When *G* has bounded treewidth, it has a tree decomposition in which all bags have bounded size, and such a decomposition can be found in fixed-parameter tractable time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Moreover, it is possible to choose this tree decomposition so that it forms a binary tree, with only two child subtrees per bag.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Therefore, it is possible to perform a bottom-up computation on this tree decomposition, computing an identifier for the equivalence class of the subtree rooted at each bag by combining the edges represented within the bag with the two identifiers for the equivalence classes of its two children.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The size of the automaton constructed in this way is not an elementary function of the size of the input MSO formula.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] This non-elementary complexity is necessary, in the sense that (unless P = NP) it is not possible to test MSO properties on trees in a time that is fixed-parameter tractable with an elementary dependence on the parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The proofs of Courcelle's theorem show a stronger result: not only can every (counting) monadic second-order property be recognized in linear time for graphs of bounded treewidth, but also it can be recognized by a finite-state tree automaton.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Courcelle conjectured a converse to this: if a property of graphs of bounded treewidth is recognized by a tree automaton, then it can be defined in counting monadic second-order logic.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] In 1998 Lapoire (1998), claimed a resolution of the conjecture.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] However, the proof is widely regarded as unsatisfactory.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Until 2016, only a few special cases were resolved: in particular, the conjecture has been proved for graphs of treewidth at most three, for k-connected graphs of treewidth k, for graphs of constant treewidth and chordality, and for k-outerplanar graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The general version of the conjecture was finally proved by Mikołaj Bojańczyk and Michał Pilipczuk.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Moreover, for Halin graphs (a special case of treewidth three graphs) counting is not needed: for these graphs, every property that can be recognized by a tree automaton can also be defined in monadic second-order logic.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The same is true more generally for certain classes of graphs in which a tree decomposition can itself be described in MSOL.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] However, it cannot be true for all graphs of bounded treewidth, because in general counting adds extra power over monadic second-order logic without counting.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] For instance, the graphs with an even number of vertices can be recognized using counting, but not without.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The satisfiability problem for a formula of monadic second-order logic is the problem of determining whether there exists at least one graph (possibly within a restricted family of graphs) for which the formula is true.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] For arbitrary graph families, and arbitrary formulas, this problem is undecidable.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] However, satisfiability of MSO2 formulas is decidable for the graphs of bounded treewidth, and satisfiability of MSO1 formulas is decidable for graphs of bounded clique-width.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The proof involves building a tree automaton for the formula and then testing whether the automaton has an accepting path.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] As a partial converse, Seese (1991) proved that, whenever a family of graphs has a decidable MSO2 satisfiability problem, the family must have bounded treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] The proof is based on a theorem of Robertson and Seymour that the families of graphs with unbounded treewidth have arbitrarily large grid minors.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Seese also conjectured that every family of graphs with a decidable MSO1 satisfiability problem must have bounded clique-width; this has not been proven, but a weakening of the conjecture that replaces MSO1 by CMSO1 is true.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Grohe (2001) used Courcelle's theorem to show that computing the crossing number of a graph *G* is fixed-parameter tractable with a quadratic dependence on the size of *G*, improving a cubic-time algorithm based on the Robertson–Seymour theorem.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] An additional later improvement to linear time by Kawarabayashi & Reed (2007) follows the same approach.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] If the given graph *G* has small treewidth, Courcelle's theorem can be applied directly to this problem.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] On the other hand, if *G* has large treewidth, then it contains a large grid minor, within which the graph can be simplified while leaving the crossing number unchanged.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Grohe's algorithm performs these simplifications until the remaining graph has a small treewidth, and then applies Courcelle's theorem to solve the reduced subproblem.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Gottlob & Lee (2007) observed that Courcelle's theorem applies to several problems of finding minimum multi-way cuts in a graph, when the structure formed by the graph and the set of cut pairs has bounded treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] As a result they obtain a fixed-parameter tractable algorithm for these problems, parameterized by a single parameter, treewidth, improving previous solutions that had combined multiple parameters.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] In computational topology, Burton & Downey (2014) extend Courcelle's theorem from MSO2 to a form of monadic second-order logic on simplicial complexes of bounded dimension that allows quantification over simplices of any fixed dimension.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] As a consequence, they show how to compute certain quantum invariants of 3-manifolds as well as how to solve certain problems in discrete Morse theory efficiently, when the manifold has a triangulation (avoiding degenerate simplices) whose dual graph has small treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/courcelle-s-theorem] Methods based on Courcelle's theorem have also been applied to database theory, knowledge representation and reasoning, automata theory, and model checking.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] A **parameterized approximation algorithm** is a type of algorithm that aims to find approximate solutions to NP-hard optimization problems in polynomial time in the input size and a function of a specific parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] These algorithms are designed to combine the best aspects of both traditional approximation algorithms and fixed-parameter tractability.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] In traditional approximation algorithms, the goal is to find solutions that are at most a certain factor α away from the optimal solution, known as an α-approximation, in polynomial time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] On the other hand, parameterized algorithms are designed to find exact solutions to problems, but with the constraint that the running time of the algorithm is polynomial in the input size and a function of a specific parameter k.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The parameter describes some property of the input and is small in typical applications.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The problem is said to be fixed-parameter tractable (FPT) if there is an algorithm that can find the optimum solution in $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ time, where $f(k)$ is a function independent of the input size n.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] A parameterized approximation algorithm aims to find a balance between these two approaches by finding approximate solutions in FPT time: the algorithm computes an α-approximation in $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ time, where $f(k)$ is a function independent of the input size n.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] This approach aims to overcome the limitations of both traditional approaches by having stronger guarantees on the solution quality compared to traditional approximations while still having efficient running times as in FPT algorithms.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] An overview of the research area studying parameterized approximation algorithms can be found in the survey of Marx and the more recent survey by Feldmann et al.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] For example, some problems that are APX-hard and W[1]-hard admit a **parameterized approximation scheme (PAS)**, i.e., for any $\varepsilon >0$ a $(1+\varepsilon )$ -approximation can be computed in $f(k,\varepsilon )n^{g(\varepsilon )}$ time for some functions f and g.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] This then circumvents the lower bounds in terms of polynomial-time approximation and fixed-parameter tractability.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] A PAS is similar in spirit to a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS) but additionally exploits a given parameter k.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Since the degree of the polynomial in the runtime of a PAS depends on a function $g(\varepsilon )$ , the value of $\varepsilon$ is assumed to be arbitrary but constant in order for the PAS to run in FPT time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] If this assumption is unsatisfying, $\varepsilon$ is treated as a parameter as well to obtain an **efficient** **parameterized approximation scheme (EPAS)**, which for any $\varepsilon >0$ computes a $(1+\varepsilon )$ -approximation in $f(k,\varepsilon )n^{O(1)}$ time for some function f.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] This is similar in spirit to an efficient polynomial-time approximation scheme (EPTAS).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The *k*-cut problem has no polynomial-time $(2-\varepsilon )$ -approximation algorithm for any $\varepsilon >0$ , assuming ${\mathsf {P}}\neq {\mathsf {NP}}$ and the small set expansion hypothesis.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] It is also W[1]-hard parameterized by the number k of required components.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However an EPAS exists, which computes a $(1+\varepsilon )$ -approximation in $(k/\varepsilon )^{O(k)}n^{O(1)}$ time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The Travelling Salesman problem is APX-hard and paraNP-hard parameterized by the doubling dimension (as it is NP-hard in the Euclidean plane).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However, an EPAS exists parameterized by the doubling dimension, and even for the more general highway dimension parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The Steiner Tree problem is FPT parameterized by the number of terminals.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However, for the "dual" parameter consisting of the number k of non-terminals contained in the optimum solution, the problem is W[2]-hard (due to a folklore reduction from the Dominating Set problem).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Steiner Tree is also known to be APX-hard.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The more general Steiner Forest problem is NP-hard on graphs of treewidth 3.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However, on graphs of treewidth t an EPAS can compute a $(1+\varepsilon )$ -approximation in $2^{O({\frac {t^{2}}{\varepsilon }}\log {\frac {t}{\varepsilon }})}n^{O(1)}$ time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] It is known that the Strongly Connected Steiner Subgraph problem is W[1]-hard parameterized by the number k of terminals, and also does not admit an $O(\log ^{2-\varepsilon }n)$ -approximation in polynomial time (under standard complexity assumptions).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However a 2-approximation can be computed in $3^{k}n^{O(1)}$ time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Furthermore, this is best possible, since no $(2-\varepsilon )$ -approximation can be computed in $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ time for any function f, under Gap-ETH.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Matching parameterized approximation algorithms exist, but it is not known whether matching approximations can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Clustering is often considered in settings of low dimensional data, and thus a practically relevant parameterization is by the dimension of the underlying metric.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] In the Euclidean space, the k-Median and k-Means problems admit an EPAS parameterized by the dimension d, and also an EPAS parameterized by k.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The former was generalized to an EPAS for the parameterization by the doubling dimension.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] For the loosely related highway dimension parameter, only an approximation scheme with XP runtime is known to date.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] For the metric *k*-center problem a 2-approximation can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However, when parameterizing by either the number k of centers, the doubling dimension (in fact the dimension of a Manhattan metric), or the highway dimension, no parameterized $(2-\varepsilon )$ -approximation algorithm exists, under standard complexity assumptions.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Furthermore, the k-Center problem is W[1]-hard even on planar graphs when simultaneously parameterizing it by the number k of centers, the doubling dimension, the highway dimension, and the pathwidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However, when combining k with the doubling dimension an EPAS exists, and the same is true when combining k with the highway dimension.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] For the more general version with vertex capacities, an EPAS exists for the parameterization by k and the doubling dimension, but not when using k and the highway dimension as the parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Regarding the pathwidth, k-Center admits an EPAS even for the more general treewidth parameter, and also for cliquewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] An optimization variant of the *k*-Clique problem is the Densest *k*-Subgraph problem (which is a 2-ary Constraint Satisfaction problem), where the task is to find a subgraph on k vertices with maximum number of edges.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] It is not hard to obtain a $(k-1)$ -approximation by just picking a matching of size $k/2$ in the given input graph, since the maximum number of edges on k vertices is always at most ${k \choose 2}=k(k-1)/2$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] This is also asymptotically optimal, since under Gap-ETH no $k^{1-o(1)}$ -approximation can be computed in FPT time parameterized by k.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] For the Dominating set problem it is W[1]-hard to compute any $g(k)$ -approximation in $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ time for any functions g and f.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Kernelization is a technique used in fixed-parameter tractability to pre-process an instance of an NP-hard problem in order to remove "easy parts" and reveal the NP-hard core of the instance.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] A kernelization algorithm takes an instance I and a parameter k, and returns a new instance $I'$ with parameter $k'$ such that the size of $I'$ and $k'$ is bounded as a function of the input parameter k, and the algorithm runs in polynomial time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] An **α-approximate kernelization algorithm** is a variation of this technique that is used in parameterized approximation algorithms.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] It returns a kernel $I'$ such that any β-approximation in $I'$ can be converted into an αβ-approximation to the input instance I in polynomial time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] This notion was introduced by Lokshtanov et al., but there are other related notions in the literature such as Turing kernels and **α**-fidelity kernelization.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] As for regular (non-approximate) kernels, a problem admits an α-approximate kernelization algorithm if and only if it has a parameterized α-approximation algorithm.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] The proof of this fact is very similar to the one for regular kernels.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] However the guaranteed approximate kernel might be of exponential size (or worse) in the input parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Hence it becomes interesting to find problems that admit polynomial sized approximate kernels.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Furthermore, a **polynomial-sized approximate kernelization scheme (PSAKS)** is an **α**-approximate kernelization algorithm that computes a polynomial-sized kernel and for which **α** can be set to $1+\varepsilon$ for any $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] For example, while the Connected Vertex Cover problem is FPT parameterized by the solution size, it does not admit a (regular) polynomial sized kernel (unless ${\textsf {NP}}\subseteq {\textsf {coNP/poly}}$ ), but a PSAKS exists.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] Similarly, the Steiner Tree problem is FPT parameterized by the number of terminals, does not admit a polynomial sized kernel (unless ${\textsf {NP}}\subseteq {\textsf {coNP/poly}}$ ), but a PSAKS exists.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-approximation-algorithm] When parameterizing Steiner Tree by the number of non-terminals in the optimum solution, the problem is W[2]-hard (and thus admits no exact kernel at all, unless FPT=W[2]), but still admits a PSAKS.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In computer science, **parameterized complexity** is a branch of computational complexity theory that focuses on classifying computational problems according to their inherent difficulty with respect to *multiple* parameters of the input or output.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The complexity of a problem is then measured as a function of those parameters.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] This allows the classification of NP-hard problems on a finer scale than in the classical setting, where the complexity of a problem is only measured as a function of the number of bits in the input.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] This appears to have been first demonstrated in Gurevich, Stockmeyer & Vishkin (1984).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The first systematic work on parameterized complexity was done by Downey & Fellows (1999).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] However, some problems can be solved by algorithms that are exponential only in the size of a fixed parameter while polynomial in the size of the input.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Under the assumption that P ≠ NP, there exist many natural problems that require super-polynomial running time when complexity is measured in terms of the input size only but that are computable in a time that is polynomial in the input size and exponential or worse in a parameter k.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Hence, if k is fixed at a small value and the growth of the function over k is relatively small then such problems can still be considered "tractable" despite their traditional classification as "intractable".
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Such an algorithm is called a fixed-parameter tractable (FPT) algorithm, because the problem can be solved efficiently (i.e., in polynomial time) for constant values of the fixed parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A parameterized problem that allows for such an FPT algorithm is said to be a **fixed-parameter tractable** problem and belongs to the class FPT, and the early name of the theory of parameterized complexity was **fixed-parameter tractability**.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Many problems have the following form: given an object x and a nonnegative integer k, does x have some property that depends on k?
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] For instance, for the vertex cover problem, the parameter can be the number of vertices in the cover.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In many applications, for example when modelling error correction, one can assume the parameter to be "small" compared to the total input size.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Then it is challenging to find an algorithm that is exponential *only* in k, and not in the input size.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In this way, parameterized complexity can be seen as *two-dimensional* complexity theory.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] when its parameter is the size of the solution to the problem.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] For example, there is an algorithm that solves the vertex cover problem in $O(kn+1.274^{k})$ time, where n is the number of vertices and k is the size of the vertex cover.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] This means that vertex cover is fixed-parameter tractable with the size of the solution as the parameter (its natural parameter).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The class **FPL** (fixed parameter linear) is the class of problems solvable in time $f(k)\cdot |x|$ for some computable function f.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] An example is the Boolean satisfiability problem, parameterised by the number of variables.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A given formula of size m with k variables can be checked by brute force in time $O(2^{k}m)$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A vertex cover of size k in a graph of order n can be found in time $O(2^{k}n)$ , so the vertex cover problem is also in FPL.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] An example of a problem that is thought not to be in FPT is graph coloring parameterised by the number of colors.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] It is known that 3-coloring is NP-hard, and an algorithm for graph k-coloring in time $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ for $k=3$ would run in polynomial time in the size of the input.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Thus, if graph coloring parameterised by the number of colors were in FPT, then P = NP.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] There are a number of alternative definitions of FPT.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] For example, the running-time requirement can be replaced by $f(k)+|x|^{O(1)}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Also, a parameterised problem is in FPT if it has a so-called kernel.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Kernelization is a preprocessing technique that reduces the original instance to its "hard kernel", a possibly much smaller instance that is equivalent to the original instance but has a size that is bounded by a function in the parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] FPT is closed under a parameterised notion of reductions called ***fpt-reductions***.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Obviously, FPT contains all polynomial-time computable problems.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Moreover, it contains all optimisation problems in NP that allow an efficient polynomial-time approximation scheme (EPTAS).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] These problems are called slicewise polynomial, in the sense that each "slice" of fixed *k* has a polynomial-time algorithm, although with a possibly different exponent for each *k*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Compare this with FPT, which merely allows a different constant prefactor for each value of k.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] XP strictly contains FPT by diagonalization.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A problem is **para-NP-hard** if it is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard already for a constant value of the parameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] That is, there is a "slice" of fixed k that is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A parameterized problem that is ${\textsf {para-NP}}$ -hard cannot belong to the class ${\textsf {XP}}$ , unless ${\textsf {P}}={\textsf {NP}}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A classic example of a ${\textsf {para-NP}}$ -hard parameterized problem is graph coloring, parameterized by the number k of colors, which is already ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard for $k=3$ (see Graph coloring#Computational complexity).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In the parameterized complexity theory, there are some hierarchies of complexity classes.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Each such class is closed under fpt-reduction.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The most important ones are the ***W* hierarchy** and the ***A* hierarchy**.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In general, there are two ways to define a complexity class: machine-theoretically and logically.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In machine theory, a class is defined as the set of decision problems solvable by a class of machines.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In logic, a class is defined as the set of decision problems definable by a class of logical formulas.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The **Hamming weight** (**weight** for short) of a binary string is the number of ones appearing in it.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A Boolean circuit is an acyclic directed graph where the nodes are one of the following gates: AND, OR, NOT.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A small gate is a gate with fan-in 0, 1, or 2.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The **weft** is the largest number of big gates achievable on any path from an input to the output.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The **depth** is the largest number of gates (small or big) achievable on any path from an input to the output.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A Boolean circuit is **monotone** iff it uses no NOT gate.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A Boolean circuit is **antimonotone** iff it is of the form $\phi (\neg x_{1},\dots ,\neg x_{n})$ where $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ are all its inputs, and $\phi$ is monotone.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] we define $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Gamma )$ to be the **parameterized model checking** problem for this tuple.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Here we see that "W" stands for "weight".
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Note that in the above definition, $w,d$ are independent of $(x,k)$ , but the circuit itself depends on $(x,k)$ , and may change if one changes either x or k .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A **normalized circuit** of weft *w* and depth *d* is a circuit, where the first $d-w$ layers contain only small gates, and the last w layers contain alternating big gates of AND and OR.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] One can iterate the associative laws and de Morgan distribution laws to normalize the circuit in fpt-time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Therefore, without loss of generality, we can consider only normalized circuits.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Model-theoretically, the class *W[t]* is defined as the class of problems fpt-reducible to $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Sigma _{t,1})$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] While the *W* hierarchy is a hierarchy contained in NP, the *A* hierarchy more closely mimics the polynomial-time hierarchy from classical complexity.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Machine-theoretically, the A hierarchy of problems are defined as problems that are fpt-reducible to computations by certain kinds of alternating Turing machines.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Model-theoretically, the class *A[t]* is defined as the class of problems fpt-reducible to $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Sigma _{t})$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] For example, the *k*-clique problem can be specified as a model checking problem.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The language has a single binary relation E , where $E(x,y)$ means " $x,y$ share an edge".
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Then, a finite model A is a graph, and it has a *k*-clique iff $A\models \phi _{k}$ , where $\phi _{k}:=\exists x_{1:k},\bigwedge _{1\leq i<j\leq n}E(x_{i},x_{j})$ This shows that the *k*-clique problem is in $A[1]$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A problem is ***A[i]*-complete** if it is *A[i]*, and any *A[i]* problem fpt-reduces to it.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Intuitively, problems in W[1] class can be interpreted of the form: Is there an object of size *k* with a certain locally-checkable property?
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] That is, a big AND over many OR of fan-in 2.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Note that the plain nonblocker problem is FPT.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Note on the nondeterministic Turing machine.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The machine may be specified by one of any of the standard formulations.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] One usually considers the one-tape Turing machine, but the short Turing machine problem remains *W[1]* even if we allow with *f*(*k*) tapes and even *f*(*k*) of *f*(*k*)-dimensional tapes, but even with this extension, the restriction to *f*(*k*) tape alphabet size is FPT.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Crucially, because the machine *M* itself is part of the problem input, the input size *n* is bigger than the number of states of *M*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] In this way, the Turing machine can take one of n possible computation paths per step, accessing $n^{O(k)}$ steps in total within time *k*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Thus, we see that *W[1]* is not obviously contained within *FPT*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The independent set problem can be encoded thus.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Given each graph $(V,E)$ , its independent set problem is encoded by the following weft-1 Boolean circuit: $\Phi _{\text{IS}}(V,E):=\bigwedge _{\{u,v\}\in E}(\neg x_{u}\lor \neg x_{v})$ where E is the set of edges in the graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The graph has an independent set of size *k* iff there is a weight-*k* input to its Boolean circuit, such that it outputs 1.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The clique problem can be coded as $\Phi _{\text{clique}}(V,E):=\bigwedge _{\{u,v\}\subset V,u\neq v,\{u,v\}\not \in E}(\neg x_{u}\lor \neg x_{v})$ It checks that any pair vertices that don't make an edge cannot be chosen, so any chosen set of vertices is forced to be a clique.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The short Turing machine problem can be converted to a Boolean formula using the same proof idea as of the Cook–Levin theorem, which shows SAT is NP-complete by coding Turing machine computational traces as Boolean formulas.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Of the indices, time *t* and tape position *p* range over *1:k*, The ranges of the indices to the Turing machine state *i, j*, transition *m*, and symbols *a, b* are determined by the description of the machine M, but they are both bounded within *1:n*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] A computational trace through the Turing machine is then fully specified by setting *k* variables of $s_{t,i,j,a,b}$ to True to indicate the Turing machine state transitions at each time, and setting $k^{2}$ variables of $y_{t,p,a,b}$ to True to indicate the tape state transition at each time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] This reduces the short Turing machine problem to a problem of finding a weight- $(k+k^{2})$ satisfying assignment to a weft-1, depth-2, antimonotone Boolean circuit.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The dominating set problem has formula $\Psi _{\text{dom}}(V,E)=\bigwedge _{u\in V}\bigvee _{v\in \operatorname {Neighbor} [u]}x_{v}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Some problems are known to be *W[i]*-complete, though they are in a computationally generic form, and are usually studied within parameterized complexity theory itself.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Empirically, as of 2013, almost all naturally-occurring parameterized problems that they have studied, turned out to be *W[0]*-complete, *W[1]*-complete, or *W[2]*-complete.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] These problems are essentially "artificial", in that they are not studied except within the context of parameterized complexity.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] It contains *W[SAT]*, since a Boolean formula can be efficiently converted to a Boolean circuit.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Note that the opposite is not true in general, since the equivalent Boolean formula to a Boolean circuit may be necessarily exponentially larger than the circuit.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Equivalently, it is the class of problems that can be decided by a nondeterministic $h(k)\cdot {|x|}^{O(1)}$ -time Turing machine that makes at most $O(f(k)\cdot \log n)$ nondeterministic choices in the computation on $(x,k)$ (a *k*-restricted Turing machine).
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] It is known that FPT is contained in W[P], and the inclusion is believed to be strict.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] However, resolving this issue would imply a solution to the P versus NP problem.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The *W** hierarchy is similar to the *W* hierarchy, but it parameterizes depth, rather than holding it constant.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] One can interpret this as a 2-player game, with the first player trying to make the circuit output True, and the second player trying to make the circuit output False.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The first player makes a move by setting exactly $k_{1}$ inputs of $I_{1}$ to True and the others to False, then the second player makes a move on $I_{2}$ , etc.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] The circuit is under alternating weight- $(k_{1},\dots ,k_{r})$ conditions iff player 1 has a winning strategy.
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] It turns out that the hierarchy collapses: $AW[1]=AW[2]=\cdots$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/parameterized-complexity] Thus, the literature writes just a common symbol for them: $AW[\ast ]:=AW[1]=AW[2]=\cdots$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] In graph theory, the **treewidth** of an undirected graph is an integer number which specifies, informally, how far the graph is from being a tree.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The smallest treewidth is 1; the graphs with treewidth 1 are exactly the trees and the forests.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] An example of graphs with treewidth at most 2 are the series–parallel graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The maximal graphs with treewidth exactly k are called *k-trees*, and the graphs with treewidth at most k are called *partial k-trees*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Many other well-studied graph families also have bounded treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Treewidth is commonly used as a parameter in the parameterized complexity analysis of graph algorithms.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Many algorithms that are NP-hard for general graphs, become easier when the treewidth is bounded by a constant.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The concept of treewidth was originally introduced by Umberto Bertelè and Francesco Brioschi (1972) under the name of *dimension*.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] It was later rediscovered by Rudolf Halin (1976), based on properties that it shares with a different graph parameter, the Hadwiger number.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Later it was again rediscovered by Neil Robertson and Paul Seymour (1984) and has since been studied by many other authors.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] A tree decomposition of a graph $G=(V,E)$ is a tree T in which each node is associated with a subset of vertices called a "bag".
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] (The term *node* is used to refer to a vertex of T to avoid confusion with vertices of G ).
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] If bags $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ both contain a vertex v , then all bags $X_{k}$ associated with nodes in the (unique) path of T between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ also contain v as well.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Equivalently, the bags containing vertex v are associated with a connected subtree of T .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For every edge $(v,w)$ in the graph, there is at least one bag $X_{i}$ that contains both v and w .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] That is, vertices are adjacent in the graph only when their corresponding subtrees have a node in common.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The *width* of a tree decomposition is the size of its largest bag $X_{i}$ minus one.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The **treewidth** $\operatorname {tw} (G)$ of a graph G is the minimum width among all possible tree decompositions of G .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] In this definition, the size of the largest set is diminished by one in order to make the treewidth of a tree equal to one.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Equivalently, the treewidth of G is one less than the size of the largest clique in the chordal graph containing G with the smallest clique number.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] A chordal graph with this clique size may be obtained by adding to G an edge between every two vertices for which at least one bag contains both vertices.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Treewidth may also be characterized in terms of havens, functions describing an evasion strategy for a certain pursuit–evasion game defined on a graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] A similar characterization can also be made using brambles, families of connected subgraphs that all touch each other (meaning either that they share a vertex or are connected by an edge).
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The order of a bramble is the smallest hitting set for the family of subgraphs, and the treewidth of a graph is one less than the maximum order of a bramble.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Every complete graph $K_{n}$ has treewidth $n-1$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] This is most easily seen using the definition of treewidth in terms of chordal graphs: the complete graph is already chordal, and adding more edges cannot reduce the size of its largest clique.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] A connected graph with at least two vertices has treewidth 1 if and only if it is a tree.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] A tree has treewidth one by the same reasoning as for complete graphs (namely, it is chordal, and has maximum clique size two).
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Conversely, if a graph has a cycle, then every chordal completion of the graph includes at least one triangle consisting of three consecutive vertices of the cycle, from which it follows that its treewidth is at least two.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For any fixed constant k , the graphs of treewidth at most k are called the partial k -trees.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Other families of graphs with bounded treewidth include the cactus graphs, pseudoforests, series–parallel graphs, outerplanar graphs, Halin graphs, and Apollonian networks.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The control-flow graphs arising in the compilation of structured programs also have bounded treewidth, which allows certain tasks such as register allocation to be performed efficiently on them.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The planar graphs do not have bounded treewidth, because the $n\times n$ grid graph is a planar graph with treewidth exactly n .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Therefore, if F is a minor-closed graph family with bounded treewidth, it cannot include all planar graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Conversely, if some planar graph cannot occur as a minor for graphs in family F , then there is a constant k such that all graphs in F have treewidth at most k .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] F is a minor-closed graph family that does not include all planar graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For every finite value of k , the graphs of treewidth at most k may be characterized by a finite set of forbidden minors.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] (That is, any graph of treewidth greater than k includes one of the graphs in the set as a minor.) Each of these sets of forbidden minors includes at least one planar graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For larger values of k , the number of forbidden minors grows at least as quickly as an exponential function of ${\sqrt {k}}$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] However, known upper bounds on the size and number of forbidden minors are much higher than this lower bound.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] It is ${\mathsf {NP}}$ -complete to determine whether a given graph G has treewidth at most a given variable k .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] However, when k is any fixed constant, the graphs with treewidth k can be recognized, and a width k tree decomposition constructed for them, in linear time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The time dependence of this algorithm on k is exponential.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Due to the roles the treewidth plays in an enormous number of fields, different practical and theoretical algorithms computing the treewidth of a graph were developed.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Depending on the application on hand, one can prefer better approximation ratio, or better dependence in the running time from the size of the input or the treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The table below provides an overview of some of the treewidth algorithms.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Here k is the treewidth and n is the number of vertices of an input graph G .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Each of the algorithms outputs in time $f(k)\cdot g(n)$ a decomposition of width given in the Approximation column.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For example, the algorithm of Bodlaender (1996) in time $2^{O(k^{3})}\cdot n$ either constructs a tree decomposition of the input graph G of width at most k or reports that the treewidth of G is more than k .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Similarly, the algorithm of Bodlaender et al.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] (2016) in time $2^{O(k)}\cdot n$ either constructs a tree decomposition of the input graph G of width at most $5k+4$ or reports that the treewidth of G is more than k .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Korhonen (2021) improved the width of the decomposition to $2k+1$ in the same running time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] It is not known whether determining the treewidth of planar graphs is NP-complete, or whether their treewidth can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] In practice, an algorithm of Shoikhet & Geiger (1997) can determine the treewidth of graphs with up to 100 vertices and treewidth up to 11, finding a chordal completion of these graphs with the optimal treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For larger graphs, one can use search-based techniques such as branch and bound search to compute the treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] These algorithms are anytime in that when stopped early, they will output an upper bound on the treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] An algorithm of this type was proposed in 2004 by Vibhav Gogate and Rina Dechter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] To provide a lower bound on treewidth for the branches of this search, they construct a graph minor by repeatedly contracting an edge between a minimum degree vertex and one of its neighbors, until just one vertex remains.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The maximum of the minimum degree over these constructed minors is guaranteed to be a lower bound on the treewidth of the graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Alex Dow and Rich Korf further improved this algorithm using best-first search.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Later, several authors independently observed at the end of the 1980s that many algorithmic problems that are NP-complete for arbitrary graphs may be solved efficiently by dynamic programming for graphs of bounded treewidth, using the tree-decompositions of these graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] As an example, the problem of coloring a graph of treewidth k may be solved by using a dynamic programming algorithm on a tree decomposition of the graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The resulting algorithm finds an optimal coloring of an n -vertex graph in time $O(k^{k+O(1)}n)$ , a time bound that makes this problem fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For a large class of problems, there is a linear time algorithm to solve a problem from the class if a tree-decomposition with constant bounded treewidth is provided.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Specifically, Courcelle's theorem states that if a graph problem can be expressed in the logic of graphs using monadic second order logic, then it can be solved in linear time on graphs with bounded treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Consider for example the 3-coloring problem for graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] For a graph $G=(V,E)$ , this problem asks if it is possible to assign each vertex $v\in V$ one of three colors such that no two adjacent vertices are assigned the same color.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The pathwidth of a graph has a very similar definition to treewidth via tree decompositions, but is restricted to tree decompositions in which the underlying tree of the decomposition is a path graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Alternatively, the pathwidth may be defined from interval graphs analogously to the definition of treewidth from chordal graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] As a consequence, the pathwidth of a graph is always at least as large as its treewidth, but it can only be larger by a logarithmic factor.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Another parameter, the graph bandwidth, has an analogous definition from proper interval graphs, and is at least as large as the pathwidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Other related parameters include the tree-depth, a number that is bounded for a minor-closed graph family if and only if the family excludes a path, and the degeneracy, a measure of the sparsity of a graph that is at most equal to its treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Because the treewidth of an $n\times n$ grid graph is n , the treewidth of a graph G is always greater than or equal to the size of the largest square grid minor of G .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] In the other direction, the *grid minor theorem* by Robertson and Seymour shows that there exists an unbounded function f such that the largest square grid minor of a graph of treewidth k has size at least $f(k)$ .
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] (For the $\Omega$ notation in the lower bound, see big O notation.) Tighter bounds are known for restricted graph families, leading to efficient algorithms for many graph optimization problems on those families through the theory of bidimensionality.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Halin's grid theorem provides an analogue of the relation between treewidth and grid minor size for infinite graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] A family F of graphs closed under taking subgraphs is said to have **bounded local treewidth**, or the **diameter-treewidth property**, if the treewidth of the graphs in the family is upper bounded by a function of their diameter.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] If the class is also assumed to be closed under taking minors, then F has bounded local treewidth if and only if one of the forbidden minors for F is an apex graph.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The original proofs of this result showed that treewidth in an apex-minor-free graph family grows at most doubly exponentially as a function of diameter; later this was reduced to singly exponential and finally to a linear bound.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Bounded local treewidth is closely related to the algorithmic theory of bidimensionality, and every graph property definable in first order logic can be decided for an apex-minor-free graph family in an amount of time that is only slightly superlinear.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] It is also possible for a class of graphs that is not closed under minors to have bounded local treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] In particular this is trivially true for a class of bounded degree graphs, as bounded diameter subgraphs have bounded size.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Another example is given by 1-planar graphs, graphs that can be drawn in the plane with one crossing per edge, and more generally for the graphs that can be drawn on a surface of bounded genus with a bounded number of crossings per edge.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] As with minor-closed graph families of bounded local treewidth, this property has pointed the way to efficient approximation algorithms for these graphs.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] Halin (1976) defines a class of graph parameters that he calls S-functions, which include the treewidth.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The set of all such functions forms a complete lattice under the operations of elementwise minimization and maximization.
[src:parameterized-complexity/treewidth] The top element in this lattice is the treewidth, and the bottom element is the Hadwiger number, the size of the largest complete minor in the given graph.
